### `ApplyCoupon`
| Mutation | Why it survives |
|----------|----------------|
| `< 1.00m` → `< 0m` (disable floor) | No test where coupon exceeds total (e.g., FLAT50 on a \$40 order) |
| Return `0m` for unknown codes | No test with an invalid coupon |
| Remove `"SAVE20"` / `"FLAT5"` branches | No tests exercise those codes |

## Recommendations

Add **boundary tests** (exact threshold values) and **feature-coverage tests** (express, heavy item, coupon floor, unknown code). For example:

```csharp
// Boundary: exactly 1000 should get 15%
Assert.AreEqual(150m, calc.CalculateDiscount(1000m));
// Just below: 999.99 should get 10%
Assert.AreEqual(99.999m, calc.CalculateDiscount(999.99m));

// Express surcharge
Assert.AreEqual(9.00m, calc.CalculateShipping(50m, 2.0, true));

// Heavy item fee (weight > 10kg)
Assert.AreEqual(25.50m, calc.CalculateShipping(50m, 11.0, false));

// Coupon floor: FLAT50 on $40 order → clamped to 1.00
Assert.AreEqual(1.00m, calc.ApplyCoupon(40m, "FLAT50"));

// Unknown coupon: no discount
Assert.AreEqual(100m, calc.ApplyCoupon(100m, "BOGUS"));
```

In short: your tests verify the "happy middle" of each branch but miss every boundary and several features entirely. A tool like [Stryker.NET](https://stryker-mutator.io/) can automate this kind of mutation analysis going forward.
